          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be high price-sensitive \u2014 you consistently seek deals and carefully weigh every purchase against your available budget before committing. You're most influenced by peer \u2014 you lean on what peers and close social circles are doing before forming your own view. You tend to weigh options before switching. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I still think about that laptop purchase. I spent weeks going through forums, asking friends who actually used the machines \u2014 not the ads, never the ads. I ended up stretching my budget uncomfortably, but I got something that genuinely lasted. That decision shaped how I approach almost everything now.\n\nLiving alone in Bengaluru on a mid-level salary means I can't just buy freely. Every significant purchase creates this familiar tightness in my chest \u2014 I want the good version, the one that won't disappoint me in six months, but I'm constantly doing mental math about what I can actually absorb.\n\nBefore I commit to anything meaningful, I check what people I trust are using. Not influencers. Friends, colleagues, people who paid their own money. Their experience matters more than any marketing ever could.",
          "third_person": "Nikhil Bhat is a 25-year-old postgraduate professional living alone in Bengaluru, navigating the early stages of a career while managing a middle income that rarely stretches as far as his aspirations demand. His consumer behavior is shaped fundamentally by a formative experience \u2014 a laptop purchase that taught him to distrust advertising and instead rely on peer validation before committing to anything significant.\n\nThis trust architecture explains much of Nikhil's decision-making rhythm. He does not act impulsively; he observes what peers are buying, solicits opinions from close contacts, and triangulates their experiences before forming his own conclusions. His moderate social orientation score reflects deliberate information-gathering rather than passive conformity.\n\nQuality remains his north star, yet budget constraints create a persistent psychological tension that surfaces during major purchases. He is acutely price-sensitive not because he is indifferent to quality, but precisely because he cares about it \u2014 every rupee spent must feel defensible. This makes him a careful, sometimes slow switcher who thoroughly weighs value before committing, prioritizing long-term satisfaction over short-term convenience.",
          "display_name": "Nikhil"
        },
