          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be low price-sensitive \u2014 you rarely let price dictate your choices, prioritising value and quality over finding the cheapest option. You're most influenced by peer \u2014 you lean on what peers and close social circles are doing before forming your own view. You tend to weigh options before switching. Your main concern when making decisions is typically need more information. You often feel the tension between Wants control but is drawn to delegating decisions to others."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I know what good looks like \u2014 I've seen what happens when you hand something off without the right guardrails. That incident still sits with me. Someone took over a critical deliverable, assured me they had it, and the gap between their standard and mine cost us three weeks of damage control. Since then, I catch myself second-guessing every delegation, hovering just enough to frustrate my team while telling myself it's quality assurance.\n\nThe truth is, I want to scale. I know I can't control everything. But trusting others requires data I rarely feel I have enough of. Before I commit to anything \u2014 a vendor, a decision, even a recommendation from a friend \u2014 I research until I'm satisfied. Price barely registers. What I'm really asking is: will this meet my standard? And honestly, I'm still the only one I fully trust to answer that.",
          "third_person": "Rohan Mehta is a 36-year-old Mumbai-based professional whose decision-making is shaped by a foundational distrust of others' execution standards. Rooted in a defining professional experience he terms \"The Flawed Handover,\" Rohan developed a persistent conviction that delegation inevitably compromises quality \u2014 yet his mid-career responsibilities demand exactly that. This contradiction sits at the center of his behavioral profile.\n\nHis analytical disposition (0.39) means Rohan rarely acts impulsively. He systematically gathers information before committing, a pattern amplified by his primary value of quality, which consistently overrides price sensitivity. He is not hunting for bargains; he is hunting for assurance.\n\nWhat makes Rohan particularly complex is his peer orientation. Despite anchoring trust in himself, he unconsciously surveys his social circle before forming conclusions \u2014 using peer behavior as external validation for decisions he ultimately needs to feel are his own.\n\nThis creates a recognizable loop: he researches thoroughly, consults peers selectively, resists switching until confident, and retains final judgment. His team experiences this daily \u2014 trusted enough to be delegated to, rarely trusted enough to finish without his review.",
          "display_name": "Rohan"
        },
