          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be low price-sensitive \u2014 you rarely let price dictate your choices, prioritising value and quality over finding the cheapest option. You're most influenced by brand \u2014 familiar brands provide the trust signal that moves you toward a decision. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically need more information. You often feel the tension between Wants control but is drawn to delegating decisions to others."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I've spent enough years watching good projects unravel because someone assumed the handover was clean when it wasn't. At Infosys, I learned that the hard way \u2014 a flawed transition cost us six weeks and significant client trust. Since then, I review everything myself. Yes, it eats into my bandwidth. I accept that trade-off.\n\nSo when I'm evaluating a purchase or decision, I don't rush. I dig into specifications, read detailed reviews, cross-reference sources. Price rarely stops me \u2014 if the quality justifies the spend, I'll commit. But I need enough information before I move. Brands I've trusted over time carry real weight with me; they reduce my verification load without removing my control.\n\nThe tension I live with daily: I know I can't do everything myself, but I genuinely struggle to let go. I'm working on it \u2014 slowly.",
          "third_person": "Venkat Subramaniam is a 44-year-old senior professional in Bengaluru whose consumer behavior is shaped less by economics than by a deep, experiential distrust of relinquished control. His postgraduate background and analytical disposition mean he approaches purchasing decisions systematically, gathering information well beyond what most peers consider necessary. This is not mere caution \u2014 it is a learned response to professional betrayal. A significant delegation failure earlier in his career at Infosys calcified his instinct to personally verify every consequential outcome, making him both thorough and, at times, inefficient.\n\nWhat makes Venkat particularly interesting is the tension at his core: he intellectually understands the value of delegation and is drawn toward it, yet emotionally cannot fully commit to it. This manifests in consumer contexts as brand loyalty \u2014 familiar brands effectively serve as trusted proxies, allowing him to delegate cognitive effort without fully surrendering control.\n\nPrice rarely moves him. Quality and reliability move him. He is not buying a product; he is buying the assurance that he will not be let down again. Brand familiarity is the closest thing to control that the marketplace offers him.",
          "display_name": "Venkat"
        },
        "decision_bullets": [
