          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be high price-sensitive \u2014 you consistently seek deals and carefully weigh every purchase against your available budget before committing. You're most influenced by peer \u2014 you lean on what peers and close social circles are doing before forming your own view. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I still think about that laptop. Bought it cheap, convinced myself it was \"good enough\" \u2014 and spent the next eighteen months dealing with overheating, dead pixels, and a battery that lasted forty minutes. The repair bills alone exceeded what I'd have paid for something decent upfront. That experience rewired me completely.\n\nNow, living alone in Chennai on a mid-level salary, every significant purchase becomes a spreadsheet in my head. I want the best \u2014 I genuinely believe quality is non-negotiable \u2014 but my bank account has its own opinion. So I research obsessively, cross-check with friends who've actually used the product, and wait for the right price window. I trust my own judgment ultimately, but I need data before I commit.\n\nThe tension never fully disappears. I'm always asking: is this worth it, or am I about to repeat that mistake?",
          "third_person": "Karthik Rajan is a 27-year-old postgraduate professional living alone in Chennai, navigating the characteristically difficult terrain of early-career financial constraints against an uncompromising appetite for quality. His decision-making is rooted in a formative experience \u2014 a defective laptop purchase that convinced him that cheap products ultimately cost more, both financially and emotionally. This single episode calcified into a governing principle that now shapes nearly every consumer choice he makes.\n\nDespite his analytical orientation, Karthik does not operate in isolation. He actively monitors peer behavior before committing to a position, using social circles as a reality-checking mechanism rather than a primary authority. This reflects a trust anchor firmly lodged in himself \u2014 he gathers peer signals, processes them critically, then arrives at conclusions independently.\n\nHis core tension is structural: he genuinely values quality but earns a middle income on a single-person household budget. This forces him into exhaustive price-value calculations before purchasing, explaining why he gravitates toward trusted brands rather than experimenting \u2014 loyalty reduces the cognitive and financial risk of getting it wrong again.",
          "display_name": "Karthik"
        },
