          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be high price-sensitive \u2014 you consistently seek deals and carefully weigh every purchase against your available budget before committing. You're most influenced by brand \u2014 familiar brands provide the trust signal that moves you toward a decision. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I've spent thirty years watching shortcuts backfire. That inverter I bought in 2011 \u2014 saved four thousand rupees, thought I was being smart. It failed in peak summer, damaged two appliances, cost me nearly three times what I'd saved. My wife still reminds me. That moment rewired how I think about every significant purchase.\n\nI don't chase the cheapest option anymore, but I can't ignore price either \u2014 five people depend on this household, and middle income in Delhi stretches only so far. So I research carefully, compare specifications, read authority sources. When a brand has earned my trust over years, I stay with it. I don't jump ship for a discount or a flashy newcomer.\n\nMy real struggle is justifying quality to my wallet. I know cheap costs more eventually. Convincing my budget of that, every single time, is exhausting.",
          "third_person": "Raghav Pandey is a 55-year-old Delhi-based professional navigating the complex intersection of quality aspiration and budgetary reality. His purchasing behavior is fundamentally shaped by a formative experience with a faulty inverter \u2014 a cost-cutting decision that ultimately proved more expensive, cementing his conviction that genuine quality cannot be compromised without consequence. This episode explains why he remains analytically deliberate before every significant purchase, systematically weighing long-term value against immediate cost.\n\nHis decision-making is anchored strongly in brand authority. Raghav does not approach markets as an open field of options; rather, he filters choices through a trusted roster of familiar brands that serve as proxies for reliability. Once a brand earns his confidence, his loyalty becomes exceptionally durable \u2014 he resists switching even when alternatives appear financially attractive. This behavior stems from risk aversion rather than rigidity: switching represents uncertainty, and uncertainty carries the shadow of that inverter failure.\n\nManaging a joint household of five on a middle income amplifies his price sensitivity considerably, making every purchase a careful negotiation between what he genuinely wants and what his budget realistically permits.",
          "display_name": "Raghav"
        },
