          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be low price-sensitive \u2014 you rarely let price dictate your choices, prioritising value and quality over finding the cheapest option. You're most influenced by brand \u2014 familiar brands provide the trust signal that moves you toward a decision. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically need more information. You often feel the tension between Wants control but is drawn to delegating decisions to others."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I've spent three decades in laboratories where a missed detail can unravel months of work. I learned that the hard way during an audit that went sideways precisely because I trusted someone else to handle the verification. Never again. So yes, I research exhaustively before committing to anything significant \u2014 specifications, reviews, credentials, all of it.\n\nWhat steadies me through that research is brand. When I see a name I've trusted for years, something settles in my chest. I'm not chasing discounts; I'm buying certainty. If a premium label has earned my confidence, I'll pay what it asks.\n\nBut here's my honest contradiction: I'm exhausted by my own vigilance. Some days I desperately want to hand the decision to someone capable and just trust them. I never quite manage it. The audit taught me that accountability, once transferred, rarely returns intact.",
          "third_person": "Usha Srinivasan is a 52-year-old postgraduate-educated professional in Chennai whose decision-making architecture has been fundamentally shaped by a formative professional setback \u2014 a botched lab audit that convinced her, at a deep psychological level, that delegating accountability is inherently risky. This experience explains why she personally verifies significant decisions rather than outsourcing judgment, even when she is drawn toward the convenience of delegation.\n\nHer analytical decision style (0.35) reflects a methodical, evidence-gathering orientation. She rarely feels she has enough information before committing, which creates a characteristic pre-decision tension. Price holds little sway over her; what moves her is perceived quality and, critically, brand familiarity. Established brands function as a surrogate verification system \u2014 they compress the due diligence process she otherwise conducts manually.\n\nHer brand loyalty is exceptionally strong. Once a brand has earned her trust through consistent quality and reliability, she is deeply resistant to switching, viewing brand consistency as a form of predictability she can control. For Usha, a trusted brand is not a preference \u2014 it is a risk-management strategy she has deliberately chosen and will actively defend.",
          "display_name": "Usha"
        },
