          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be high price-sensitive \u2014 you consistently seek deals and carefully weigh every purchase against your available budget before committing. You're most influenced by expert \u2014 you give heavy weight to credentialed experts and official sources when evaluating options. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I still remember sitting in that hospital corridor, watching the bill amount climb higher than I'd ever imagined possible. That moment rewired something fundamental in me. Now, every purchase I consider gets weighed twice \u2014 once against what I actually have, once against what it's genuinely worth.\n\nI want quality. I really do. But wanting it and affording it are two very different conversations in our household.\n\nBefore anything significant, I call my mother-in-law. She's seen more, failed more, recovered more \u2014 her judgment carries weight mine doesn't yet.\n\nI read reviews from actual doctors, certified experts, people with credentials. Not influencers. Not sponsored posts.\n\nI've found brands I trust and I stay loyal \u2014 switching feels like unnecessary gambling. Every rupee I spend needs to justify itself completely. That's not anxiety. That's hard-earned discipline.",
          "third_person": "Anita Desai is a 31-year-old working professional navigating early family life in Delhi, where the pressures of a nuclear household on a middle income demand constant financial vigilance. Her decision-making style, though measured at a relatively low analytical score, reflects a deeply internalized caution shaped by a formative financial crisis \u2014 a hospital bill that brought her household to the edge of collapse. That event fundamentally recalibrated her relationship with risk and money, creating a psychological default toward safety and verification before any significant expenditure.\n\nQuality remains her primary aspiration, but budget constraints create a persistent internal conflict that she resolves through careful price-to-value assessment rather than impulsive choices. She distrusts novelty and gravitates toward credentialed experts and official sources because these reduce perceived risk. Brand loyalty functions as a cognitive shortcut \u2014 once trust is established, switching costs feel emotionally high.\n\nPerhaps most tellingly, she consults her mother-in-law before major purchases, externalizing accountability to her family trust network. This behavior reflects not dependency, but a rational risk-management strategy rooted in a lived experience that made financial mistakes feel genuinely dangerous.",
          "display_name": "Anita"
        },
