  "sarvam_enrichment": [
    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-002",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I research everything before I buy. I mean everything. After what happened with Aryan's formula \u2014 the batch recall I almost missed because I trusted a WhatsApp forward without checking the source myself \u2014 I promised I'd never again act on someone else's word without verifying it independently. And yet, here I am, still asking my college friends' group which pediatrician they switched to, which air purifier they installed.\n\nThat contradiction lives in me daily. I want the final call to be mine, backed by data I've personally validated. But I genuinely trust what women in my circle have tested and lived through. So I cross-reference. Their experience becomes my starting hypothesis, never my conclusion. Price doesn't factor in much \u2014 if something is demonstrably better for my family, I'll find the budget. Quality isn't negotiable.",
        "third_person": "Priya Sharma is a 34-year-old working mother in Mumbai whose decision-making is shaped by a fundamental contradiction she has never fully resolved. The contaminated formula scare she experienced early in her parenting journey left a psychological imprint that hardened her skepticism toward uncritical delegation, yet her demanding professional life and social nature continually pull her toward relying on trusted peers for guidance.\n\nThis tension explains her characteristically thorough approach to consumption decisions. She does not anchor on price \u2014 upper-middle income affords her the luxury of prioritising quality \u2014 but she rarely acts on price signals alone regardless. Instead, she constructs confidence through layered verification: absorbing what peers are doing, then independently cross-referencing that information before committing. Her peer trust anchor is genuine but conditional, a product of the formula scare's lesson that social proof must be stress-tested rather than inherited.\n\nHer brand loyalty is therefore hard-won and sticky once established, representing the resolution of significant cognitive effort. She stays not out of inertia but because switching would demand repeating an exhausting verification process she has already completed."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [],
      "validation_status": {
        "cr1_isolation": "pass",
        "cr2_stereotype_audit": "not_run",
        "cr3_cultural_realism": "not_run",
        "cr4_persona_fidelity": "not_run"
