    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-001",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still think about that laptop. Bought the cheaper one to save six thousand rupees, and it died eight months in \u2014 right before a project deadline. I lost data, I lost sleep, and honestly, I lost a bit of faith in my own judgment. That moment rewired something in me.\n\nNow I'm sitting in a one-bedroom in Whitefield, single income, no safety net beyond my own salary. Every major purchase becomes this exhausting internal negotiation. I'll spend two weeks on 91mobiles forums and tech subreddits, cross-checking reviews, asking people in my network what they actually use daily. Peer opinions matter more to me than any advertisement.\n\nI want the best version of whatever I'm buying. I just can't always afford it. So I wait, I research, I calculate \u2014 and I try not to repeat old mistakes.",
        "third_person": "Arjun Menon is a 29-year-old software professional living alone in Whitefield, Bengaluru, navigating the familiar tension of early-career ambition against financial constraint. His analytical decision style \u2014 reflected in a moderate but deliberate score of 0.35 \u2014 means he rarely acts on impulse. Instead, he constructs mental frameworks around every significant purchase, mapping quality indicators against budget thresholds before committing.\n\nThis behavior is deeply rooted in a formative experience: a defective budget laptop that failed at a critical moment in Koramangala, teaching him that compromising on core tools carries hidden costs far exceeding initial savings. That incident calcified his primary value around durability, even as his middle income demands ongoing price sensitivity.\n\nWhat makes Arjun particularly compelling as a consumer is his trust architecture. He extends confidence not to brands or advertisements, but to peer consensus \u2014 91mobiles discussions, tech forums, and word-of-mouth from friends carry disproportionate weight in his evaluations. He will spend considerable time researching before switching products or services, treating community validation as a proxy for quality assurance. His decisions are slow, deliberate, and defensively rational."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "91mobiles forums (Karnataka tech community hub, traceable to: location.city, education.postgraduate, employment.full-time)",
        "Whitefield (specific Bengaluru locality, traceable to: location.region, life_story.age_28)",
