    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-010",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I never make a purchase without running the numbers at least twice. After spending three sleepless weeks restructuring my thesis because I rushed a methodology decision, I learned that corners cut early cost everything later. So now I cross-reference everything \u2014 99acres reviews, Amazon Q&A threads, peer opinions from my office Slack \u2014 before committing a single rupee.\n\nLiving alone in Chennai on a mid-level salary means every decision carries real weight. I genuinely want quality. Not luxury, just things that actually work and last \u2014 like my Kindle from college that still runs, or a good steel tumbler from Nilgiris. But my budget doesn't always agree with my standards, and that gap frustrates me constantly.\n\nI trust my colleagues and friends more than any advertisement. When Priya from my office recommends something she's actually used, that matters more than a brand's marketing claims. I'm not impulsive \u2014 I'm thorough. Because I know exactly what happens when you're not.",
        "third_person": "Divya Krishnaswamy is a 28-year-old postgraduate professional living alone in Chennai, navigating early career life on a middle-income salary. Her decision-making is deeply shaped by a formative academic crisis during her Anna University thesis revision, an experience that installed a near-compulsive need to verify and cross-check before committing to any choice. This explains her moderately analytical orientation \u2014 she researches exhaustively on 99acres, Amazon product Q&A, and Flipkart reviews before committing, weighing quality signals against budget constraints with deliberate care.\n\nHer primary value is quality, yet her income reality introduces persistent friction. This tension does not paralyze her; rather, it channels her energy toward exhaustive research aimed at finding the highest quality option within an acceptable price range. She sources from trusted Chennai retailers like Nilgiris and Spencer's, where peer recommendations from her office circle validate product reliability. Once a brand earns her confidence through consistent quality delivery, her loyalty becomes notably stable, reducing the cognitive load of repeated decision-making."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "99acres (Indian property/review platform used for product research)",
