    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-013",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still think about that ThinkPad purchase. I spent weeks on Reddit threads and tech forums, messaging friends who actually owned them \u2014 not the ads, never the ads. I ended up stretching my first paycheck uncomfortably, but I got something that genuinely lasted. That decision shaped how I approach almost everything now.\n\nLiving alone in Bengaluru on a mid-level salary means I can't just buy freely. Every significant purchase creates this familiar tightness in my chest \u2014 I want the quality version, the one that won't disappoint me in six months, but I'm constantly doing mental math about what I can actually absorb.\n\nBefore I commit to anything meaningful, I check what people I trust are using. Not influencers. Friends, colleagues from the office, people who paid their own money. Their experience matters more than any marketing ever could.",
        "third_person": "Nikhil Bhat is a 25-year-old postgraduate professional living alone in Bengaluru, navigating the early stages of a data analytics career while managing a middle income that rarely stretches as far as his aspirations demand. His consumer behavior is shaped fundamentally by a formative experience \u2014 a ThinkPad purchase researched across tech forums and Reddit threads that taught him to distrust advertising and instead rely on peer validation before committing to anything significant.\n\nThis trust architecture explains much of Nikhil's decision-making rhythm. He does not act impulsively; he observes what peers and colleagues are buying, solicits opinions from close contacts, and triangulates their experiences before forming his own conclusions. His moderate social orientation reflects deliberate information-gathering rather than passive conformity.\n\nQuality remains his north star, yet budget constraints create a persistent psychological tension that surfaces during major purchases. He is acutely price-sensitive not because he is indifferent to quality, but precisely because he cares about it \u2014 every rupee spent must feel defensible. This makes him a careful, sometimes slow switcher who thoroughly weighs value before committing, prioritizing long-term satisfaction over short-term convenience."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "ThinkPad (specific model choice over generic laptop)",
        "Reddit threads (Bengaluru tech community platform)",
        "data analytics career (postgraduate field specificity)",
        "office colleagues (Bengaluru metro workplace context)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
