    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-009",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I know what good looks like \u2014 I've seen what happens when you hand something off without the right guardrails. That incident still sits with me. Someone took over a critical client deliverable, assured me they had it, and the gap between their standard and mine cost us a \u20b940-lakh contract renewal and three weeks of damage control. Since then, I catch myself second-guessing every delegation, hovering just enough to frustrate my team while telling myself it's quality assurance.\n\nThe truth is, I want to scale. I know I can't control everything. But trusting others requires data I rarely feel I have enough of. Before I commit to anything \u2014 a vendor, a decision, even a recommendation from peers in my circle \u2014 I research until I'm satisfied. Price barely registers. What I'm really asking is: will this meet my standard? And honestly, I'm still the only one I fully trust to answer that.",
        "third_person": "Rohan Mehta is a 36-year-old Mumbai-based consulting professional whose decision-making is shaped by a defining professional experience at age 28\u2014a critical client deliverable delegated to a junior team member that resulted in an error-laden report costing the firm a \u20b940-lakh contract renewal. This incident crystallized his conviction that delegation inevitably compromises quality, yet his mid-career responsibilities demand exactly that. This contradiction sits at the center of his behavioral profile.\n\nHis analytical disposition means Rohan rarely acts impulsively. Before purchasing his 2BHK in Powai at 32, he systematized comparisons across 23 apartments, EMI scenarios, and builder track records\u2014a rigor that yielded 18% appreciation while peers who rushed faced delays. He is not hunting for bargains; he is hunting for assurance. Despite anchoring trust in his own judgment\u2014honed through self-studying CAT for 14 months and rejecting coaching centre advice\u2014he unconsciously surveys his social circle before forming conclusions. His team experiences this daily: trusted enough to be delegated to, rarely trusted enough to finish without his review."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "\u20b940-lakh contract renewal (income-scaled business reference)",
        "2BHK in Powai (Mumbai micro-location, upper-middle aspirational landmark)",
        "CAT exam (postgraduate education pathway, India-specific MBA entrance)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "critical client deliverable, assured me they had it",
          "replacement": "critical client deliverable costing \u20b940 lakhs",
          "attribute_source": "life_story.age_28"
        },
        {
          "original": "an apartment",
          "replacement": "a 2BHK in Powai",
          "attribute_source": "location.city + life_story.age_32"
        },
        {
          "original": "self-studied for months",
          "replacement": "self-studied for 14 months for CAT",
          "attribute_source": "life_story.age_24 + education.postgraduate"
        }
      ],
      "validation_status": {
        "cr1_isolation": "pass",
        "cr2_stereotype_audit": "not_run",
        "cr3_cultural_realism": "not_run",
        "cr4_persona_fidelity": "not_run"
      },
      "skip_reason": null
    },
    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-007",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I've spent enough years watching good projects unravel because someone assumed the handover was clean when it wasn't. At Infosys, I learned that the hard way \u2014 a flawed transition cost us six weeks and significant client trust. Since then, I review everything myself. Yes, it eats into my bandwidth. I accept that trade-off.\n\nSo when I'm evaluating a purchase or decision, I don't rush. I dig into specifications, read detailed reviews on 99acres or Property Shark, cross-reference sources. Price rarely stops me \u2014 if the quality justifies the spend, I'll commit. But I need enough information before I move. Brands I've trusted over time \u2014 Bosch, Ceat, HDFC Life \u2014 carry real weight with me; they reduce my verification load without removing my control.\n\nThe tension I live with daily: I know I can't do everything myself, but I genuinely struggle to let go. I'm working on it \u2014 slowly.",
        "third_person": "Venkat Subramaniam is a 44-year-old senior professional in Bengaluru whose consumer behavior is shaped less by economics than by a deep, experiential distrust of relinquished control. His postgraduate background and analytical disposition mean he approaches purchasing decisions systematically, gathering information well beyond what most peers consider necessary \u2014 consulting property databases, RERA portals, and detailed reviews before committing. This is not mere caution; it is a learned response to professional betrayal. A significant delegation failure earlier in his career at Infosys calcified his instinct to personally verify every consequential outcome, making him both thorough and, at times, inefficient.\n\nWhat makes Venkat particularly interesting is the tension at his core: he intellectually understands the value of delegation and is drawn toward it, yet emotionally cannot fully commit to it. This manifests in consumer contexts as brand loyalty to established Indian and multinational names \u2014 Bosch, Ceat, HDFC Life \u2014 allowing him to delegate cognitive effort without fully surrendering control. Price rarely moves him. Quality and reliability move him. He is not buying a product; he is buying the assurance that he will not be let down again."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "99acres (Bengaluru property portal, upper-middle income)",
        "Property Shark (verification tool, traces to Whitefield flat purchase life story)",
        "Bosch (trusted appliance brand, upper-middle income, quality-focused)",
        "Ceat (trusted automotive/industrial brand, quality-first purchasing behavior)",
        "HDFC Life (trusted financial services brand, risk-averse investment behavior)",
        "RERA portals (institutional verification, traces to property purchase due diligence)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "read detailed reviews",
          "replacement": "read detailed reviews on 99acres or Property Shark",
          "attribute_source": "location.city + income_bracket + life_story.property_purchase"
        },
        {
          "original": "Brands I've trusted over time carry real weight with me",
          "replacement": "Brands I've trusted over time \u2014 Bosch, Ceat, HDFC Life \u2014 carry real weight with me",
          "attribute_source": "income_bracket (upper-middle) + behavioral_summary (brand loyalty, quality-focused)"
        },
        {
          "original": "consulting sources",
          "replacement": "consulting property databases, RERA portals, and detailed reviews",
          "attribute_source": "life_story.property_purchase (4-month due diligence on Whitefield flat)"
        }
      ],
      "validation_status": {
        "cr1_isolation": "pass",
        "cr2_stereotype_audit": "not_run",
        "cr3_cultural_realism": "not_run",
        "cr4_persona_fidelity": "not_run"
