    },
    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-003",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still think about that laptop. Bought it cheap from some reseller in Ritchie Street, convinced myself it was \"good enough\" \u2014 and spent the next eighteen months dealing with overheating, dead pixels, and a battery that lasted forty minutes. The repair bills at Spencer Plaza alone exceeded what I'd have paid for something decent upfront. That experience rewired me completely.\n\nNow, living alone in Chennai on a mid-level salary, every significant purchase becomes a spreadsheet in my head. I want the best \u2014 I genuinely believe quality is non-negotiable \u2014 but my bank account has its own opinion. So I research obsessively on 91mobiles or Flipkart reviews, cross-check with friends who've actually used the product, and wait for the right price window. I trust my own judgment ultimately, but I need data before I commit.\n\nThe tension never fully disappears. I'm always asking: is this worth it, or am I about to repeat that mistake?",
        "third_person": "Karthik Rajan is a 27-year-old postgraduate professional living alone in Chennai, navigating the characteristically difficult terrain of early-career financial constraints against an uncompromising appetite for quality. His decision-making is rooted in a formative experience \u2014 a defective budget laptop from Ritchie Street that convinced him cheap products ultimately cost more, both financially and emotionally. This single episode calcified into a governing principle that now shapes nearly every consumer choice he makes.\n\nDespite his analytical orientation, Karthik does not operate in isolation. He actively monitors peer behavior \u2014 what colleagues at his firm trust, what reviews surface on 91mobiles or Amazon India \u2014 before committing to a position, using social circles as a reality-checking mechanism rather than a primary authority. This reflects a trust anchor firmly lodged in himself: he gathers peer signals, processes them critically, then arrives at conclusions independently.\n\nHis core tension is structural: he genuinely values quality but earns a middle income on a single-person household budget. This forces him into exhaustive price-value calculations before purchasing, explaining why he gravitates toward trusted brands rather than experimenting \u2014 loyalty reduces the cognitive and financial risk of getting it wrong again."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Ritchie Street (Chennai electronics market)",
        "Spencer Plaza (Chennai shopping landmark)",
        "91mobiles (Indian product review platform)",
        "Flipkart reviews (Indian e-commerce ecosystem)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "Bought it cheap, convinced myself it was \"good enough\"",
          "replacement": "Bought it cheap from some reseller in Ritchie Street, convinced myself it was \"good enough\"",
          "attribute_source": "location.city"
        },
        {
          "original": "The repair bills alone exceeded what I'd have paid",
          "replacement": "The repair bills at Spencer Plaza alone exceeded what I'd have paid",
          "attribute_source": "location.city"
        },
        {
          "original": "cross-check with friends who've actually used the product",
          "replacement": "cross-check with friends who've actually used the product, and wait for the right price window on 91mobiles or Flipkart",
          "attribute_source": "behavioural_summary.peer_influence + location.metro"
        }
      ],
      "validation_status": {
        "cr1_isolation": "pass",
        "cr2_stereotype_audit": "not_run",
        "cr3_cultural_realism": "not_run",
        "cr4_persona_fidelity": "not_run"
      },
      "skip_reason": null
    },
    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-017",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I've spent thirty years watching shortcuts backfire. That inverter I bought in 2011 \u2014 some no-name brand my brother-in-law swore by \u2014 saved four thousand rupees, thought I was being smart. It failed in peak summer, damaged two appliances, cost me nearly three times what I'd saved. My wife still reminds me. That moment rewired how I think about every significant purchase.\n\nI don't chase the cheapest option anymore, but I can't ignore price either \u2014 five people depend on this household, and middle income in Delhi stretches only so far. So I research carefully, compare specifications, read reviews on Consumer Reports India or check trusted institutional recommendations like my State Bank manager did for me years ago. When a brand like Bajaj or Havells has earned my trust over years, I stay with it. I don't jump ship for a discount or a flashy newcomer.\n\nMy real struggle is justifying quality to my wallet. I know cheap costs more eventually. Convincing my budget of that, every single time, is exhausting.",
        "third_person": "Raghav Pandey is a 55-year-old Delhi-based professional navigating the complex intersection of quality aspiration and budgetary reality. His purchasing behavior is fundamentally shaped by a formative experience with a faulty inverter \u2014 a cost-cutting decision that ultimately proved more expensive, cementing his conviction that genuine quality cannot be compromised without consequence. This episode explains why he remains analytically deliberate before every significant purchase, systematically weighing long-term value against immediate cost through institutional sources like Consumer Reports India.\n\nHis decision-making is anchored strongly in brand authority. Raghav does not approach markets as an open field of options; rather, he filters choices through a trusted roster of familiar brands \u2014 Bajaj, Havells, State Bank of India \u2014 that serve as proxies for reliability in Delhi's middle-class household economy. Once a brand earns his confidence, his loyalty becomes exceptionally durable \u2014 he resists switching even when alternatives appear financially attractive. This behavior stems from risk aversion rather than rigidity: switching represents uncertainty, and uncertainty carries the shadow of that inverter failure.\n\nManaging a joint household of five on a middle income amplifies his price sensitivity considerably, making every purchase a careful negotiation between what he genuinely wants and what his budget realistically permits."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "State Bank manager (institutional authority figure from life story age 32)",
        "Bajaj (trusted appliance brand, Delhi metro market standard)",
        "Havells (trusted electrical brand, Delhi metro market standard)",
        "Consumer Reports India (institutional authority source aligned with research behavior)",
        "joint household economic constraint (from household.structure)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "some no-name brand my brother-in-law swore by",
          "replacement": "some no-name brand my brother-in-law swore by",
          "attribute_source": "life_story.age_38 (inverter purchase, brother-in-law recommendation)"
        },
        {
          "original": "read authority sources",
          "replacement": "read reviews on Consumer Reports India or check trusted institutional recommendations like my State Bank manager did for me years ago",
          "attribute_source": "behavioral_summary.influence + life_story.age_32 (SBI fixed deposit decision)"
        },
