    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-018",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I've spent three decades in pharmaceutical labs where a missed detail can unravel months of work\u2014I learned that the hard way during a regulatory audit that went sideways precisely because I trusted someone else to handle the verification. Never again. So yes, I research exhaustively before committing to anything significant\u2014specifications, reviews, credentials, all of it. I'll spend weeks cross-referencing against CDSCO guidelines or faculty credentials the way I once did for my daughter's school in Adyar.\n\nWhat steadies me through that research is brand. When I see a name I've trusted for years\u2014Himalaya, Godrej, Titan\u2014something settles in my chest. I'm not chasing discounts; I'm buying certainty. If a premium label has earned my confidence, I'll pay what it asks.\n\nBut here's my honest contradiction: I'm exhausted by my own vigilance. Some days I desperately want to hand the decision to someone capable and just trust them. I never quite manage it. The audit taught me that accountability, once transferred, rarely returns intact.",
        "third_person": "Usha Srinivasan is a 52-year-old postgraduate-educated pharmaceutical professional in Chennai whose decision-making architecture has been fundamentally shaped by a formative professional setback\u2014a botched regulatory audit at a Chennai pharma firm that convinced her, at a deep psychological level, that delegating accountability is inherently risky. This experience explains why she personally verifies significant decisions rather than outsourcing judgment, even when she is drawn toward the convenience of delegation.\n\nHer analytical decision style reflects a methodical, evidence-gathering orientation characteristic of late-career Tamil professionals in regulated sectors. She rarely feels she has enough information before committing, creating pre-decision tension. Price holds little sway; what moves her is perceived quality and, critically, brand familiarity. Established Indian brands\u2014Godrej, Himalaya, Titan, HDFC Bank\u2014function as surrogate verification systems, compressing the due diligence process she otherwise conducts manually. Her brand loyalty is exceptionally strong. Once a brand has earned her trust through consistent quality, she is deeply resistant to switching, viewing brand consistency as predictability she can control. For Usha, a trusted brand is not preference\u2014it is a deliberate risk-management strategy."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
