    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-008",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still remember sitting in that hospital corridor at Max, watching the bill amount climb higher than I'd ever imagined possible. That moment rewired something fundamental in me. Now, every purchase I consider gets weighed twice \u2014 once against what I actually have, once against what it's genuinely worth.\n\nI want quality. I really do. But wanting it and affording it are two very different conversations in our household.\n\nBefore anything significant, I call my mother-in-law. She's seen more, failed more, recovered more \u2014 her judgment carries weight mine doesn't yet.\n\nI read reviews from actual doctors, certified experts, people with credentials. Not influencers. Not sponsored posts. I check ConsumerAffairs and Apollo's health guides.\n\nI've found brands I trust \u2014 Fortune oil, Amul, Himalaya \u2014 and I stay loyal. Switching feels like unnecessary gambling. Every rupee I spend needs to justify itself completely. That's not anxiety. That's hard-earned discipline.",
        "third_person": "Anita Desai is a 31-year-old working professional navigating early family life in a DDA flat in Dwarka, where the pressures of a nuclear household on a middle income demand constant financial vigilance. Her decision-making style reflects a deeply internalized caution shaped by a formative financial crisis \u2014 a neonatal ICU bill at a Delhi hospital that brought her household to the edge of collapse. That event fundamentally recalibrated her relationship with risk and money, creating a psychological default toward safety and verification before any significant expenditure.\n\nQuality remains her primary aspiration, but budget constraints create a persistent internal conflict that she resolves through careful price-to-value assessment rather than impulsive choices. She distrusts novelty and gravitates toward credentialed experts and official sources \u2014 medical journals, regulatory certifications \u2014 because these reduce perceived risk. Brand loyalty functions as a cognitive shortcut; once trust in established Indian brands is established, switching costs feel emotionally high.\n\nAs the trusted product advisor in her 200-member residents' group, she externalizes accountability through both family consultation and community validation, reflecting a rational risk-management strategy rooted in lived experience that made financial mistakes feel genuinely dangerous."
      },
